04095nam a22006735i 9780292763906DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211999txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927639067 a10.7560/7658942doi  a(DE-B1597)588211  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aN7483.P86A3 1999 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a947.0840921 aPunin, Nikolay, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Diaries of Nikolay Punin :b1904-1953 /cNikolay Punin; ed. by Jennifer Greene Krupala, Sidney Monas. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1999  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroductory Essay: Nikolay Punin and Russian Futurism -- tIntroductory Essay: Punin and Akhmatova -- tNote on the Translation -- tEarly Materials from the Punin Diaries, 1904-1910 -- tNotebook One, 1915-1917 -- tI Notebook Two, 1919 -1920 -- tNotebook Three, 1920 -- tNotebook Four, 1921-1922 -- tNotebook Five, 1922-1923 -- tNotebook Six, 1923-1924 -- tNotebook Seven, 1924 -- tNotebook Eight, 1924-1925 -- tNotebook Nine, 1925-1926 -- tNotebook Ten, 1936 -- tLate Materials from the Punin Diaries, 1941-1952 -- tGlossary -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNikolay Punin (1888-1953) was the most articulate Russian/Soviet art critic of the 1920s. He strongly advocated Constructivism, an avant-garde impulse that favored mechanomorphic abstraction and proclaimed a movement to bring art into the center of popular life. In the United States, he is perhaps best remembered for his love affair with Anna Akhmatova, one of the great poets of the twentieth century. This volume presents the first English translation of ten diary notebooks that Punin wrote between 1915 and 1936, as well as selections from his earlier (1904-1910) and later (1941-1946) diaries and some thirty notes and letters relating to his affair with Anna Akhmatova. These materials offer a rare glimpse into the life of art and artists in Russia. They also present vivid scenes from the 1905 Revolution, World War I, the 1917 Revolutions, World War II, and Stalinist oppression through the reflections of a talented man, who, unlike many of his generation, lived to tell the tale.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aArt critics-Russia (Federation)-Diaries. 0aPunin, N. N.-(Nikolaĭ Nikolaevich)-Diaries. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aGreene Krupala, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrupala, Jennifer Greene, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMonas, Sidney, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMonas, Sidney, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/76589440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292763906423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292763906/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK